The RomanS, however, did not long remain subject to the Etruri- ans. After the conquest of Rome, ArrunS, the son of Porsena, pro- ceeded to attack Aricia, but was defeated before that city by the united forces of the Latin citieS, assisted by the Greeks of Cumae. The Etrurians appear, in consequence, to have been confined to their- own territory on the right bank of the Tiber, and the Romans to have availed themselves of the opportunity to recover their independ- ence. ·

The object of Porsena's expedition against Rome is said to have been the restoration of the 'l‘arquinS, and it is natural that such ¹ should have been the belief in later timeS, happening as the war did within a year or two of the establishment of the republic. But if such had been its real object, the Tarquins must have been restored to Rome on the conquest of the city.
